# Cursor IDE Rules & Best Practices

This file defines the rules and best practices for AI assistance in this project when using Cursor IDE.

## Package Management

**IMPORTANT**: This project uses `uv` as the package manager, not pip or poetry.

- Use `uv pip install <package>` to install packages
- Use `uv pip compile` for requirements management
- Use `uv run` to execute scripts in the virtual environment
- All dependency management should be done through `uv`

## Task Runner (Makefile)

**IMPORTANT**: This project uses `make` as the task runner. Use it instead of running commands directly.

To see all available commands: `make help`

### Common Commands

**Setup & Installation:**
- `make setup` - Setup complete dev environment (install deps + hooks)
- `make install` - Install all dependencies including dev
- `make install-hooks` - Install pre-commit hooks

**Code Quality (via pre-commit):**
- `make check` - Run all pre-commit hooks (comprehensive quality checks)
- `make fix` - Fix all auto-fixable issues (lint + format)
- `make lint` - Run ruff linter via pre-commit
- `make format` - Format code with ruff via pre-commit

**Testing:**
- `make test` - Run tests with pytest
- `make test-cov` - Run tests with coverage report
- `make test-file FILE=<file>` - Run specific test file

**Jupyter Notebooks:**
- `make jupyter` - Start JupyterLab server
- `make jupyter-install-kernel` - Register project kernel
- `make lint-notebooks` - Lint notebook code cells via pre-commit (nbqa)
- `make format-notebooks` - Format notebook code with ruff
- `make strip-notebooks` - Strip outputs from notebooks via pre-commit

**Application:**
- `make run` - Run the application
- `make dev` - Run with auto-reload (development mode)

**Docker:**
- `make docker-up-dev` - Start dev container with hot reloading
- `make docker-test` - Run tests in container

**Maintenance:**
- `make clean` - Clean all generated files
- `make update` - Update dependencies
- `make pre-commit` - Run pre-commit hooks on all files

### When to Use Make

**Always use `make` commands instead of:**
- ❌ `pytest` → ✅ `make test`
- ❌ `ruff check .` → ✅ `make lint`
- ❌ `pre-commit run --all-files` → ✅ `make check`
- ❌ `jupyter lab` → ✅ `make jupyter`
- ❌ `nbqa ruff notebooks/` → ✅ `make lint-notebooks`

This ensures:
- Consistent command execution via pre-commit
- Proper virtual environment activation
- Correct flags and configurations are applied
- All quality checks run through pre-commit hooks

## Python Standards

### Style & Formatting
- Follow PEP 8 style guidelines
- Use `ruff` for linting and formatting
- Maximum line length: 100 characters
- Use 4 spaces for indentation (never tabs)

### Type Hints
- Add type hints to ALL function signatures
- Use modern Python 3.13+ typing features
- Type hint return values, including `None`

### Documentation
- Add docstrings to all public functions, classes, and modules
- Use Google-style docstrings
- Include: description, Args, Returns, Raises

For canonical coding standards and anti-pattern IDs (Y/Z + PY/PZ), use:
- `.claude/context/coding-standards.md` (entrypoint to full catalogs and topic pages)

## Jupyter Notebooks

### Notebook Organization
- Keep notebooks in `notebooks/exploratory/` for ad-hoc analysis
- Use `notebooks/experiments/` for structured experiments
- Name notebooks with dates and descriptive titles: `YYYY-MM-DD_topic.ipynb`

### Notebook Standards
- Select "GenX Enablement (Python 3.13)" kernel for all notebooks
- Follow same code quality standards as Python modules
- Restart kernel and run all cells before committing

### Version Control
- Outputs are automatically stripped via nbstripout pre-commit hooks
- Use `make strip-notebooks` to manually strip outputs
- Consider using Jupytext for better version control

### Code Quality
- Run `make lint-notebooks` and `make format-notebooks`
- Pre-commit hooks automatically check notebook quality

## Testing Standards

### Test-Driven Development
- Write tests BEFORE implementation
- Tests should be in `tests/` directory
- Use `pytest` as the testing framework
- Aim for >80% code coverage

## Documentation-First Approach

Before implementing features:
1. Document the problem in `artifacts/tickets/[TICKET-ID]/spec.md`
2. Create architecture decisions in `artifacts/architecture/`
3. Plan implementation in `artifacts/tickets/[TICKET-ID]/plan.md`

## AI-Friendly Patterns

- Maintain clear `AGENTS.md` and `CLAUDE.md` files
- Write code that clearly expresses intent
- Use descriptive variable and function names
- Follow patterns from `docs/prompt-playbook.md`

## Code Review Standards

Before committing code, verify:
- [ ] All pre-commit hooks pass (`make check`)
- [ ] All tests pass (`make test`)
- [ ] Code coverage is maintained (`make test-cov`)
- [ ] Documentation is updated

**Quick pre-commit check:**
```bash
make check && make test
```

Note: `make check` runs all pre-commit hooks including:
- Ruff linting and formatting
- Notebook linting and formatting
- File quality checks (trailing whitespace, EOF, YAML, TOML)
- nbstripout (strips notebook outputs)

## Project Structure

Maintain this directory structure:
```
.
├── .github/              # CI/CD and GitHub automation
├── .claude/              # Claude Code commands and rules
├── .cursor/              # Cursor IDE configuration
├── artifacts/            # Design and planning artifacts
├── docs/                 # Project documentation
├── instructions/         # Best practice guidelines
├── notebooks/            # Jupyter notebooks
│   ├── exploratory/      # Ad-hoc data analysis
│   └── experiments/      # Structured experiments
├── genx_enablement/      # Main Python package
├── tests/                # Test files
├── AGENTS.md             # Agent-specific instructions
├── CLAUDE.md             # Project context for Claude
├── Makefile              # Task runner commands
├── pyproject.toml        # Project config & dependencies
└── README.md             # Main project documentation
```

---

For more detailed guidelines, refer to:
- `.claude/rules.md` for comprehensive rules
- `instructions/best-practices-*.md` for specific topics
